{"key":"post-9697708","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>9697708</id>\n<content>There's no way that a half gallon jar is going to colonize without air.&amp;nbsp; If there's no source for filtered gas exchange, you're pretty much screwed, no matter how much inoculant got sucked out of your syringe.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;About all you can do is put the jar in a glovebox, wipe it down with alcohol, and punch three or four holes in the lid with a flame sterilized nail, and then cover with two layers of micropore medical tape.&amp;nbsp; When you punch the holes, punch through an alcohol soaked paper towel or cotton swab, to prevent contaminants being drawn in.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;As an alternative to micropore tape and holes, you can cut a piece of tyvek quite a bit larger than the lid of the jar, steam sterilize it, and then wrap it over the top and use a large hose clamp or several heavy-duty rubber bands to seal the tyvek to the glass side of the jar.&amp;nbsp; Then, loosen the lid on the jar half a turn, once the tyvek is in place.&amp;nbsp; This latter method is probably your best solution.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>9699148</next>\n<prev>9697264</prev>\n<first>9697024</first>\n<last>9699148</last>\n<when>1233209445</when>\n<utime>01/29/09 08:10 AM</utime>\n</post>"}